Accessing the data

AmesURL <- 'https://www.openintro.org/stat/data/ames.csv'
Ames <- read.csv(url(AmesURL), sep = ",", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
names(Ames) <- gsub('\\.', '', names(Ames))

Dimensions of the data

dim(Ames)

Identify the outliers in the original data set.We can see 5 outliers in the below plot.

plot(Ames$SalePrice, Ames$GrLivArea)

Remove the outliers in the data set

Ames <- Ames[-c(1499, 2181, 2182, 1761, 1768), ]
plot(Ames$SalePrice, Ames$GrLivArea)

We can eliminate the NAs by replacing with the median value of the column.

medianLotFrontage <- median(Ames$LotFrontage, na.rm = TRUE)
medianMasVnrArea <- median(Ames$MasVnrArea, na.rm = TRUE)
medianBsmtFinSF1 <- median(Ames$BsmtFinSF1, na.rm = TRUE)
medianBsmtFinSF2 <- median(Ames$BsmtFinSF2, na.rm = TRUE)
medianBsmtUnfSF <- median(Ames$BsmtUnfSF, na.rm = TRUE)
medianTotalBsmtSF <- median(Ames$TotalBsmtSF, na.rm = TRUE)
medianGarageYrBlt <- median(Ames$GarageYrBlt, na.rm = TRUE)
medianGarageArea <- median(Ames$GarageArea, na.rm = TRUE)

Ames$LotFrontage[is.na(Ames$LotFrontage)] <- medianLotFrontage
Ames$MasVnrArea[is.na(Ames$MasVnrArea)] <- medianMasVnrArea
Ames$BsmtFinSF1[is.na(Ames$BsmtFinSF1)] <- medianBsmtFinSF1
Ames$BsmtFinSF2[is.na(Ames$BsmtFinSF2)] <- medianBsmtFinSF2
Ames$BsmtUnfSF[is.na(Ames$BsmtUnfSF)] <- medianBsmtUnfSF
Ames$TotalBsmtSF[is.na(Ames$TotalBsmtSF)] <- medianTotalBsmtSF
Ames$GarageYrBlt[is.na(Ames$GarageYrBlt)] <- medianGarageYrBlt
Ames$GarageArea[is.na(Ames$GarageArea)] <- medianGarageArea

Distribution plot of the target showing the mean and median

SalePrice is the target feature in the Ames data set. It is possible to get a sense of the distribution of sales prices between 2006 and 2010 for the entire area.

library(repr)
options(repr.plot.width=20, repr.plot.height=8)
hist_with_kde <- function (feature) {
    plot <- qplot(feature, geom="histogram", bins=200, alpha=I(.4), y = ..density..)+
        geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(feature, rm.na=T)), color="red", linetype="dashed", size=1)+
        geom_vline(aes(xintercept=median(feature)), color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)+
       annotate(geom = 'text', x = 215000, y = 0.00000875, label = 'Mean') +
        annotate(geom = 'text', x = 124000, y = 0.00000875, label = 'Median') +
        geom_density()+ scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::dollar) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)
    return(plot)
}
hist_with_kde(Ames$SalePrice)

With the above techniques applied we can observe the most important features.These features are selected for the Principal component analysis.PCA will determine which combinations of these features will be important for our analysis.

Principal Component Analysis

The direction of PC1 indicates the line along which the data vary the most.PC2 is the linear combination of the same 11 features that is uncorrelated to PC1. Because of this, the direction of PC2 is perpendicular to the direction of PC1.Because PC1 and PC2 are orthogonal, they contain more information combined than either one does individually.The way PCA works, PC1 contains the most information.

AmesPCAMeths <- as.tibble(AmesDumScaleDF[, c(15, 12, 17, 16, 33, 9, 19, 7, 250, 172, 27)])

In Clustering We have an idea of how many PCs are important to our understanding of the Ames data structure, so we can use clustering to confirm our findings. We will use a k-means cluster method so it is important to measure clusters in terms appropriate for k-means analysis.

dis <- dist(AmesPCAMeths)^2
res <- kmeans(AmesPCAMeths, 4)
sil <- silhouette(res$cluster, dis)
windows()
plot(sil)

The silhouette chart indicates the four PCs tend to cluster well together, especially PC1 in which all cluster in the same direction. In PC2, PC3, and PC4 most clustering is in the positive direction.We can consider the four clusters from a different perspective with scatterplots.
